744. ‘The Lar of Pergamus' is the Tutelary spirit of the family, the Founder worshipped, especially in the domestic rite. Pergameus, from Troy of course.

cana Vesta, generally taken to mean ‘hoary' and so ‘ancient⁷: but Vergil applies it twice to Vesta, and once to Fides, and it probably means ‘white' ‘pure ², which seems more poetical.

The hearth or ‘shrine’ of Vesta, with its never dying fire, was the centre of the family worship, or the worship of the nation regarded as a family. The Vestal fire of Rome was always supposed to have been brought by Aeneas from Troy.

745. farre pio, ‘sacred meal' the pius being transferred (as often) from the person to the thing.
